# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cornelia-müller
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] Kendon was born on 4 April 1934 in London, son of the writer Frank Kendon and Elizabeth Cecilia Phyllis Horne, a school teacher.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] At the University of Cambridge, he read Botany, Zoology and Human Physiology, as well as Experimental Psychology for the Natural Sciences.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] At the University of Oxford, he studied Experimental Psychology, focusing on the temporal organization of utterances in conversation, using Eliot Chapple's chronography.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] Then he moved to Cornell University to study directly with Chapple on research leading to his D.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] His thesis topic—communication conduct in face-to-face interaction—spelled out the interests he would pursue in subsequent decades.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] He is noted for his study of gesture and sign languages and how these relate to spoken language.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] Phil., he accepted a position in the Institute of Experimental Psychology at Oxford, where he worked in a research group with Michael Argyle and E.R.W.F.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] He initially focused on sign systems in Papua New Guinea and Australian Aboriginal sign languages, before developing a general framework for understanding gestures with the same kind of rigorous semiotic analysis as has been previously applied to spoken language.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] Important influences on his theoretical understandings included: Erving Goffman, Albert Scheflen, Ray Birdwhistell, and Gregory Bateson.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] Becoming aware of Scheflen's work in 1965, while still at Oxford, he managed to meet him in Philadelphia, where he shared his earliest work; as a result, he was first invited to join William S.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] Condon's research team at the Western Psychiatric Institute and Clinic in 1966-67, and then to join Scheflen's research team at Bronx State Hospital in 1967.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] He never actually worked with Birdwhistell directly, but they were in contact, and he did work with films made available to him by Birdwhistell.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] In 1976 he took up an appointment in Canberra, Australia at the Department of Anthropology in the Research School of Pacific Studies, Australian National University.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] He undertook filming everyday interaction in Papua New Guinea but also was able to record a sign language in use in the valley where he worked where there was a considerable number of deaf persons.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] His publication of this work, in three articles in 1980, proved to be a pioneering study; no other accounts on sign language from this part of the world were to appear until the beginning of the twenty-first century.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] This work was republished as a monograph together with a new essay written by colleagues bringing the original work up to date.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] After this he undertook a major investigation of the sign languages in use among indigenous Australians - these are sign languages used for ritual reasons or for practical reasons in situations where speech might is impractical or inappropriate.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] These are known as alternate sign languages, distinguishing them from primary sign languages developed among deaf people.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] Extensive documentation of his research in Australia is available at the library of the Australian Institute of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] In 1988, he returned to Philadelphia, teaching for two years at the Annenberg School for Communication at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] Kendon then moved to Naples, Italy and undertook fieldwork on the use of gesture in everyday interaction among Neapolitans and also published a translation of a 19th Century book about Neapolitan gesture (by Andrea de Jorio), comparing it to gesturing among the Greeks and Romans.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] In 2004 he published an important general book on the phenomena of gesture which drew extensively on his work in Naples as well as his work in New Guinea and Australia, the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] Since then he has published various articles on gesture and related topics, including discussions of the place of gesture in theories about language origins.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] In 2012, he returned to Cambridge, where he spent the rest of his life, associated with the Division of Biological Anthropology at Cambridge, and an Honorary Professor in Psychology and Language Sciences at University College London.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] Kendon received research grants from the National Science Foundation, the Wenner-Gren Foundation for Anthropological Research, the American Council of Learned Societies, as well as a Guggenheim Fellowship.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] In addition to teaching at Oxford and Penn, he held positions at Cornell University and Connecticut College in the US, as well as the Università degli Studi di Napoli "L'Orientale", the University of Salerno and the University of Calabria in Italy.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] Kendon was a founding editor of the journal *GESTURE* (published by John Benjamins of Amsterdam), along with Cornelia Müller, in 2000.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] He was the sole editor from 2010 to April 2017, when he was replaced by Sotaro Kita.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] In his role as editor of *GESTURE* he was an Ex Officio member of the board of the International Society for Gesture Studies, of which he was elected Honorary President in 2006.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] He edited the book series *Gesture Studies* for John Benjamins, with 9 volumes published between 2007 and 2022.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] Colleagues prepared a festschrift in 2014, honoring his contribution to the study of gestures and interaction.
[src:cornelia-müller/adam-kendon] Kendon married Margaret Rhoads in 1961; they had three children, Gudrun, Benjamin and Angus.
[src:cornelia-müller/benjamins] John Benjamins is especially noted for its publications in language, linguistics, translation studies, political linguistics and literary studies.
[src:cornelia-müller/benjamins] John Benjamins publishes in print as well as online.
[src:cornelia-müller/benjamins] John Benjamins Publishing Company is a member of these professional and trade organizations: STM Association, ALPSP, UKSG, Mediafederatie-MEVW, CrossRef.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] The name of the city means *Ford of the Franks*, and a Gallic rooster appears in the coats of arms of both Frankfurt and Słubice.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] The official name *Frankfurt (Oder)* and the older *Frankfurt an der Oder* are used to distinguish it from the larger city of Frankfurt am Main (lit.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] The site of present-day Frankfurt originated as a West Slavic settlement on the Oder River.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] Following the eastward expansion of the Margraviate of Brandenburg in the 13th century, Frankfurt developed as a merchant town within Brandenburg.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] It received town privileges in 1253 and became an important trading center.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] After World War II, the eastern part of Frankfurt became part of Poland under the terms of the Potsdam Agreement and was renamed to Słubice, while the western part of Frankfurt became a border city of the German Democratic Republic in 1949.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] During the communist era, Frankfurt reached a population peak with more than 87,000 inhabitants at the end of the 1980s.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] Following German reunification, the population decreased significantly, but has stabilized in recent years at about 58,000 inhabitants.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] As of 2020, the city plays an important role in German–Polish relations and European integration.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] Frankfurt is home to the European University Viadrina, which has a campus in Słubice, the Collegium Polonicum.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] Prior to 1249, a West Slavic settlement named Zliwitz along with the Lubusz Land was part of the Kingdom of Poland.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] The Piast duke Henry the Bearded granted Zliwitz staple rights in 1225.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] Nicholas Church (today's *Friedenskirche*) began.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] In 1249, the settlement became part of the Margraviate of Brandenburg.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] The town of Frankfurt received its charter in 1253 at the Brandendamm.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] The early settlers lived on the western banks of the Oder; later the town was extended to the eastern bank.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] After a war broke out over control of the region in 1319, the town came under the control of the Duchy of Pomerania.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] In 1319, Wartislaw IV, Duke of Pomerania, granted new privileges to the town.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] The town fell again to Brandenburg in 1324.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] In the Late Middle Ages, the town dominated the river trade between Wrocław and Szczecin.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] In 1430, Frankfurt joined the Hanseatic League.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] In 1432, the Czech Hussites captured the town.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] In the 16th century, many Polish exports, including grain, wood, ash, tar and hemp, were floated from western Poland via Frankfurt to the port of Szczecin, with the high Brandenburgian customs duties on Polish goods lowered in the early 17th century.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] In April 1631, during the Thirty Years' War, Frankfurt was the site of the Battle of Frankfurt an der Oder between the Swedish Empire and the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] After a two-day siege, Swedish forces, supported by Scottish auxiliaries, stormed the town and destroyed many buildings, e.g. the Georgen Hospital.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] By the end of the Thirty Years' War, the town's population had decreased from 12,000 inhabitants to 2,366 inhabitants.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] In the 16th century the oldest church of the town (today's *Friedenskirche*) was secularized and was even used as a granary, and from the 17th century it served as the church of the French Huguenots.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] The city was briefly occupied by the Russian Imperial Army during the Seven Years' War, in August 1759, in the prelude to the battle of Kunersdorf.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] With the dissolution of the Margraviate of Brandenburg during the Napoleonic Wars, Frankfurt became part of the Province of Brandenburg in 1815.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] In the 19th century, Frankfurt played an important role in trade.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] Centrally positioned in the Kingdom of Prussia between Berlin and Posen (Poznań), on the river Oder with its heavy traffic, the town housed the second-largest annual trade fair (*Messe*) of the German Reich, surpassed only by that in Leipzig.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] One of the main escape routes for insurgents of the unsuccessful Polish November Uprising from partitioned Poland to the Great Emigration led through the city.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] In 1842, the Berlin–Frankfurt (Oder) railway was opened.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] The SS *Einsatzgruppe VI* was formed in the town before it entered several Polish cities, including Poznań, Kalisz and Leszno, to commit various crimes against Poles during the German invasion of Poland, which started World War II.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] During World War II the Germans brought numerous forced laborers, both men and women, from Poland and the Soviet Union to the town.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] In early 1945, death marches of prisoners of various nationalities from the dissolved camps in Żabikowo and Świecko to the Sachsenhausen concentration camp passed through the city.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] There was no fighting for the town in 1945 during World War II even though the town was declared a fortress (*Festung*) in an attempt to block the Red Army's route to Berlin.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] The nearly empty town was burned down by the Red Army.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] The postwar East German–Polish border ran along the Oder, separating the *Dammvorstadt* on the eastern bank – which became the Polish town of Słubice – from the rest of Frankfurt.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] While part of communist East Germany, Frankfurt was administered within Bezirk Frankfurt (Oder).
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] It became part of the reconstituted state of Brandenburg with German reunification in 1990.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] In the post-communist era, following the collapse of its main employer VEB Halbleiterwerk, Frankfurt has suffered from high unemployment and low economic growth.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] Its population has fallen significantly from around 87,000 at the time of German reunification in 1990.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] The only remnant of semiconductor technology industries in Frankfurt by 2003 was the Innovations for High Performance Microelectronics (IHPM) institute.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] Today, the towns of Frankfurt and Słubice have friendly relations and run several common projects and facilities.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] Poland joined the European Union on 1 May 2004, and implemented the Schengen Agreement on 21 December 2007 leading to the removal of permanent border controls.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] In March 2008, the Jewish community of Frankfurt celebrated its first Torah dedication since the Holocaust.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] The procession of the new Torah scroll began from the spot where the town's Frankfurter Synagogue stood prior to World War II, 500 meters from Germany's current border with Poland.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] Celebrants marched with the scroll into the town's Chabad-Lubavitch centre, where they danced with the Torah, which had been donated by members of the Chabad-Lubavitch community in Berlin.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] The Margraviate of Brandenburg's first university was Frankfurt's Alma Mater Viadrina, founded in 1506 by Joachim I Nestor, Elector of Brandenburg.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] An early chancellor, Bishop Georg von Blumenthal (1490–1550), was a notable opponent of the Protestant Reformation, as he remained a Catholic.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] Frankfurt also trained the noted archbishop Albert of Brandenburg around 1510, who also became a vocal opponent of the Reformation.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] The university was closed in 1811, and its assets divided between two new universities founded under King Frederick William III: Frederick William University of Berlin, presently Humboldt University; and the Silesian Frederick William University in Breslau, presently the University of Wrocław.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] The university was refounded in 1991 with a European emphasis as the Viadrina European University, in close cooperation with the Adam Mickiewicz University in Poznań; they jointly run the Collegium Polonicum in Słubice.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] The Frankfurt (Oder) Bahnhof is a station served by the Berlin-Warszawa-Express and has regular regional connections to Eberswalde, Guben, Leipzig, Magdeburg and Cottbus.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] Within the city, there is a network of five tram lines (including bus services).
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] The nearest airport is Berlin Brandenburg Airport which is located 80 km (50 mi) away.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] The handball club Frankfurter HC has won the German Championship once, as well as several East German Championships.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] Frankfurt (Oder), being located on the border to Poland, plays a special role in connection with German–Polish relations and European integration.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] The European University Viadrina has one of its buildings in Poland, in the neighbouring town of Słubice.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] The university also has a number of projects and initiatives dedicated to bringing Poland and Germany together, and offers its students pro bono Polish courses.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] The current mayor is René Wilke (independent, formerly Left) since 2018.
[src:cornelia-müller/frankfurt-oder] The city council governs the city alongside the mayor.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] A **gesture** is a form of nonverbal communication or non-vocal communication in which visible bodily actions communicate particular messages, either in place of, or in conjunction with, speech.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Gestures include movement of the hands, face, or other parts of the body.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Gestures differ from physical non-verbal communication that does not communicate specific messages, such as purely expressive displays, proxemics, or displays of joint attention.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Gestures allow individuals to communicate a variety of feelings and thoughts, from contempt and hostility to approval and affection, often together with body language in addition to words when they speak.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Gesticulation and speech work independently of each other, but join to provide emphasis and meaning.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Gesture processing takes place in areas of the brain such as Broca's and Wernicke's areas, which are used by speech and sign language.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] In fact, language is thought by some scholars to have evolved in *Homo sapiens* from an earlier system consisting of manual gestures.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] The theory that language evolved from manual gestures, termed Gestural Theory, dates back to the work of 18th-century philosopher and priest Abbé de Condillac, and has been revived by contemporary anthropologist Gordon W.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Hewes, in 1973, as part of a discussion on the origin of language.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Gestures have been studied throughout time from different philosophers.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Marcus Fabius Quintilianus was a Roman Rhetorician who studied in his Institutio Oratoria on how gesture can be used on rhetorical discourses.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] One of his greatest works and foundation for communication was the "Institutio Oratoria" where he explains his observations and nature of different oratories.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] A study done in 1644, by John Bulwer an English physician and early Baconian natural philosopher wrote five works exploring human communications pertaining to gestures.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Bulwer analyzed dozens of gestures and provided a guide under his book named Chirologia which focused on hand gestures.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] In the 19th century, Andrea De Jorio an Italian antiquarian who considered a lot of research about body language published an extensive account of gesture expressions.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Meltzoff an American psychologist internationally renown for infant and child development conducted a study in 1977 on the imitation of facial and manual gestures by newborns.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] The study concluded that "infants between 12 and 21 days of age can imitate the facial and manual gestures of parents".
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] A peer-reviewed journal Gesture has been published since 2001, and was founded by Adam Kendon and Cornelia Müller.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] The International Society for Gesture Studies (ISGS) was founded in 2002.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Gesture has frequently been taken up by researchers in the field of dance studies and performance studies in ways that emphasize the ways they are culturally and contextually inflected.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Performance scholar Carrie Noland describes gestures as "learned techniques of the body" and stresses the way gestures are embodied corporeal forms of cultural communication.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] But rather than just residing within one cultural context, she describes how gestures migrate across bodies and locations to create new cultural meanings and associations.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] She also posits how they might function as a form of "resistance to homogenization" because they are so dependent on the specification of the bodies that perform them.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Gesture has also been taken up within queer theory, ethnic studies and their intersections in performance studies, as a way to think about how the moving body gains social meaning.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] José Esteban Muñoz uses the idea of gesture to mark a kind of refusal of finitude and certainty and links gesture to his ideas of ephemera.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Muñoz specifically draws on the African-American dancer and drag queen performer Kevin Aviance to articulate his interest not in what queer gestures might mean, but what they might perform.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Juana María Rodríguez borrows ideas of phenomenology and draws on Noland and Muñoz to investigate how gesture functions in queer sexual practices as a way to rewrite gender and negotiate power relations.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] She also connects gesture to Giorgio Agamben's idea of "means without ends" to think about political projects of social justice that are incomplete, partial, and legibile within culturally and socially defined spheres of meaning.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Since the late 1990s, most research has revolved around the contrasting hypothesis that Lexical gestures serve a primarily cognitive purpose in aiding the process of speech production.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] As of 2012, there is research to suggest that Lexical Gesture does indeed serve a primarily communicative purpose and cognitive only secondary, but in the realm of socio-pragmatic communication, rather than lexico-semantic modification.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Humans have the ability to communicate through language, but they can also express through gestures.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] In particular, gestures can be transmitted through movements of body parts, face, and body expressions.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Researchers Goldin Meadow and Brentari D. conducted research in 2015 and concluded that communicating through sign language is no different from spoken language.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] The first way to distinguish between categories of gesture is to differentiate between communicative gesture and informative gesture.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] While most gestures can be defined as possibly happening during the course of spoken utterances, the informative-communicative dichotomy focuses on intentionality of meaning and communication in co-speech gesture.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Informative gestures are passive gestures that provide information about the speaker as a person and not about what the speaker is trying to communicate.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Some movements are not purely considered gestures, however a person could perform these adapters in such way like scratching, adjusting clothing, and tapping.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] These gestures can occur during speech, but they may also occur independently of communication, as they are not a part of active communication.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] While informative gestures may communicate information about the person speaking (e.g. itchy, uncomfortable, etc.), this communication is not engaged with any language being produced by the person gesturing.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Army recruitment poster of Uncle Sam, he is pointing and sending a non-verbal form of gesture by implying he wants the viewer to join the U.S.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] This is a form of symbolic gesture, usually used in the absence of speech.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Body language is a form of nonverbal communication that allows visual cues that transmit messages without speaking.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Gestures are movement that are made with the body: arms, hands, facial, etc.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Barbara and Allan Pease, authors of *The Definitive Book of Body Language*, concluded that everyone does a shoulder shrug, a gesture signifying that the person is not comprehending what they are supposed to be understanding.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Also, that showing the palms of both hands to show a person is not hiding anything, and raising the eyebrows to indicate a greeting.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Finger gestures are commonly used in a variety of ways, from point at something to indicate that you want to show a person something to indicating a thumbs up to show everything is good.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Some gestures are near universals, i.e., found all over the world with only some exceptions.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] An example is the head shake to signify "no".
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Also, in most cultures nodding your head signifies "Yes", which the book "The Definitive Book of Body Language" describes as submissive gesture to representing the conversation is going the direction of the person speaking.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] The book explains that people who are born deaf can show a form of submissive gesture to signify "Yes".
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Within the realm of communicative gestures, the first distinction to be made is between gestures made with the hands and arms, and gestures made with other parts of the body.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Examples of Non-manual gestures may include head nodding and shaking, shoulder shrugging, and facial expression, among others.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Non-manual gestures are attested in languages all around the world, but have not been the primary focus of most research regarding co-speech gesture.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] A gesture that is a form of communication in which bodily actions communicate particular messages.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] The most familiar are the so-called emblems or quotable gestures.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] These are conventional, culture-specific gestures that can be used as replacement for words, such as the handwave used in the US for "hello" and "goodbye".
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] A single emblematic gesture can have a very different significance in different cultural contexts, ranging from complimentary to highly offensive.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] The page List of gestures discusses emblematic gestures made with one hand, two hands, hand and other body parts, and body and facial gestures.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Symbolic gestures can occur either concurrently or independently of vocal speech.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Symbolic gestures are iconic gestures that are widely recognized, fixed, and have conventionalized meanings.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Deictic gestures can occur simultaneously with vocal speech or in place of it.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Deictic gestures are gestures that consist of indicative or pointing motions.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] These gestures often work in the same way as demonstrative words and pronouns like "this" or "that".
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Deictic gestures can refer to concrete or intangible objects or people.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Motor or beat gestures usually consist of short, repetitive, rhythmic movements that are closely tied with prosody in verbal speech.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Unlike symbolic and deictic gestures, beat gestures cannot occur independently of verbal speech and convey no semantic information.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] For example, some people wave their hands as they speak to emphasize a certain word or phrase.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] These gestures are closely coordinated with speech.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] The so-called beat gestures are used in conjunction with speech and keep time with the rhythm of speech to emphasize certain words or phrases.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] These types of gestures are integrally connected to speech and thought processes.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Other spontaneous gestures used during speech production known as iconic gestures are more full of content, and may echo, or elaborate, the meaning of the co-occurring speech.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] They depict aspects of spatial images, actions, people, or objects.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] For example, a gesture that depicts the act of throwing may be synchronous with the utterance, "He threw the ball right into the window." Such gestures that are used along with speech tend to be universal.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] For example, one describing that they are feeling cold due to a lack of proper clothing and/or a cold weather can accompany their verbal description with a visual one.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] This can be achieved through various gestures such as by demonstrating a shiver and/or by rubbing the hands together.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] The elaboration of lexical gestures falls on a spectrum of iconic-metaphorical in how closely tied they are to the lexico-semantic content of the verbal speech they coordinate with.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Lexical gestures, like motor gestures, cannot occur independently of verbal speech.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] The purpose of lexical gestures is still widely contested in the literature with some linguists arguing that lexical gestures serve to amplify or modulate the semantic content of lexical speech, or that it serves a cognitive purpose in aiding in lexical access and retrieval or verbal working memory.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Most recent research suggests that lexical gestures serve a primarily socio-pragmatic role.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Studies affirm a strong link between gesture typology and language development.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Young children under the age of two seem to rely on pointing gestures to refer to objects that they do not know the names of.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Once the words are learned, they eschewed those referential (pointing) gestures.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] One would think that the use of gesture would decrease as the child develops spoken language, but results reveal that gesture frequency increased as speaking frequency increased with age.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] There is, however, a change in gesture typology at different ages, suggesting a connection between gestures and language development.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Children most often use pointing and adults rely more on iconic and beat gestures.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] As children begin producing sentence-like utterances, they also begin producing new kinds of gestures that adults use when speaking (iconics and beats).
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Evidence of this systematic organization of gesture is indicative of its association to language development.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Gestural languages such as American Sign Language operate as complete natural languages that are gestural in modality.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] They should not be confused with finger spelling, in which a set of emblematic gestures are used to represent a written alphabet.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Sign languages are different from gesturing in that concepts are modeled by certain hand motions or expressions and has a specific established structure while gesturing is more malleable and has no specific structure rather it supplements speech.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Before an established sign language was created in Nicaragua after the 1970s, deaf Nicaraguans would use "home signs" in order to communicate with others.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] These home signs were not part of a unified language but were still used as familiar motions and expressions used within their family—still closely related to language rather than gestures with no specific structure.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Home signs are similar to the gestural actions of chimpanzees.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Gestures are used by these animals in place of verbal language, which is restricted in animals due to their lacking certain physiological and articulation abilities that humans have for speech.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] The function of gestures may have been a significant player in the evolution of language.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Gesturing is probably universal; there has been no report of a community that does not gesture.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Gestures are a crucial part of everyday conversation such as chatting, describing a route, negotiating prices on a market; they are ubiquitous.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Gestures are learned embodied cultural practices that can function as a way to interpret ethnic, gender, and sexual identity.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Gestures, commonly referred to as "body language", play an important role in industry.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Proper body language etiquette in business dealings can be crucial for success.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] However, gestures can have different meanings according to the country in which they are expressed.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] In an age of global business, diplomatic cultural sensitivity has become a necessity.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Gestures that we take as innocent may be seen by someone else as deeply insulting.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Gestures are also a means to initiate a mating ritual.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] This may include elaborate dances and other movements.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Gestures play a major role in many aspects of human life.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Additionally, when people use gestures, there is a certain shared background knowledge.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Different cultures use similar gestures when talking about a specific action such as how we gesture the idea of drinking out of a cup.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] When an individual makes a gesture, another person can understand because of recognition of the actions/shapes.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Gestures have been documented in the arts such as in Greek vase paintings, Indian Miniatures or European paintings.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Gestures play a central role in religious or spiritual rituals.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] In Hinduism and Buddhism, a *mudra* (Sanskrit, literally "seal", "gesture" or "attitude") is a symbolic gesture made with the hand, body or mind.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Each mudra has a specific meaning, and is associated with a specific spiritual quality or state.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] In yoga, mudras are considered to be higher practices which lead to awakening of the pranas, chakras and kundalini, and which can bestow major siddhis, psychic powers, on the advanced practitioner.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] In Hindu and Buddhist iconography mudras play a central role.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] For example, Vitarka Vicara, the gesture of discussion and transmission of Buddhist teaching, is done by joining the tips of the thumb and the index together, while keeping the other fingers straight.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] A common Christian religious gesture is crossing oneself as a sign of respect, also known as making the sign of the cross; often this is accompanied by kneeling before a sacred object.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] In the renewal of the Catholic liturgy promoted by the Second Vatican Council in the 1960s, "actions, gestures, and bodily attitudes" were noted as means by which a whole worshipping community could participate in the liturgical action.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Gestures are processed in the same areas of the brain as speech and sign language such as the left inferior frontal gyrus (Broca's area) and the posterior middle temporal gyrus, posterior superior temporal sulcus and superior temporal gyrus (Wernicke's area).
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] It has been suggested that these parts of the brain originally supported the pairing of gesture and meaning and then were adapted in human evolution "for the comparable pairing of sound and meaning as voluntary control over the vocal apparatus was established and spoken language evolved".
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] As a result, it underlies both symbolic gesture and spoken language in the present human brain.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Their common neurological basis also supports the idea that symbolic gesture and spoken language are two parts of a single fundamental semiotic system that underlies human discourse.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] The linkage of hand and body gestures in conjunction with speech is further revealed by the nature of gesture use in blind individuals during conversation.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] This phenomenon uncovers a function of gesture that goes beyond portraying communicative content of language and extends David McNeill's view of the gesture-speech system.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] This suggests that gesture and speech work tightly together, and a disruption of one (speech or gesture) will cause a problem in the other.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Studies have found strong evidence that speech and gesture are innately linked in the brain and work in an efficiently wired and choreographed system.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] McNeill's view of this linkage in the brain is just one of three currently up for debate; the others declaring gesture to be a "support system" of spoken language or a physical mechanism for lexical retrieval.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Because of this connection of co-speech gestures—a form of manual action—in language in the brain, Roel Willems and Peter Hagoort conclude that both gestures and language contribute to the understanding and decoding of a speaker's encoded message.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Because gestures aided in understanding the relayed message, there was not as great a need for semantic selection or control that would otherwise be required of the listener through Broca's area.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Gestures are a way to represent the thoughts of an individual, which are prompted in working memory.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] The researchers found that those with low capacity of working memory who were able to use gestures actually recalled more terms than those with low capacity who were not able to use gestures.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] The movement of gestures can be used to interact with technology like computers, using touch or multi-touch popularised by the iPhone, physical movement detection and visual motion capture, used in video game consoles.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] It can be recorded using kinematic methodology.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] In order to better understand the linguistic values that gestures hold, Adam Kendon, a pioneer in gesture research has proposed to look at it as a continuum from less linguistic to fully linguistic.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Using the continuum, speech declines as "the language-like properties of gestural behaviors increase and idiosyncratic gestures are replaced by socially regulated signs".
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Gestures of different kinds fall within this continuum and include spontaneous gesticulations, language-like gestures, pantomime, emblems, and sign language.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Spontaneous gesticulations are not evident without the presence of speech, assisting in the process of vocalization, whereas language-like gestures are "iconic and metaphoric, but lack consistency and are context-dependent".
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] "Language-like gesture" implies that the gesture is assuming something linguistic (Loncke, 2013).
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Pantomime falls in the middle of the continuum and requires shared conventions.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] This kind of gesture helps convey information or describe an event.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] Following pantomime are emblems, which have specific meanings to denote "feelings, obscenities, and insults" and are not required to be used in conjunction with speech.
[src:cornelia-müller/gesture] The most linguistic gesture on Kendon's continuum is sign language, where "single manual signs have specific meanings and are combined with other manual signs according to specific rules".
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Linguistics encompasses many branches and subfields that span both theoretical and practical applications.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Theoretical linguistics is concerned with understanding the universal and fundamental nature of language and developing a general theoretical framework for describing it.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Applied linguistics seeks to utilize the scientific findings of the study of language for practical purposes, such as developing methods of improving language education and literacy.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Mathematical linguistics is the application of mathematics to model phenomena and solve problems in general linguistics and theoretical linguistics.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Computational linguistics is an interdisciplinary field concerned with the computational modelling of natural language, as well as the study of appropriate computational approaches to linguistic questions.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Linguistics emerged from the field of philology, of which some branches are more qualitative and holistic in approach.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Today, philology and linguistics are variably described as related fields, subdisciplines, or separate fields of language study, but, by and large, linguistics can be seen as an umbrella term.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Linguistics is also related to the philosophy of language, stylistics, rhetoric, semiotics, lexicography, and translation.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Historical linguistics is the study of how language changes over history, particularly with regard to a specific language or a group of languages.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Western trends in historical linguistics date back to roughly the late 18th century, when the discipline grew out of philology, the study of ancient texts and oral traditions.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Historical linguistics emerged as one of the first few sub-disciplines in the field, and was most widely practised during the late 19th century.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Despite a shift in focus in the 20th century towards formalism and generative grammar, which studies the universal properties of language, historical research today still remains a significant field of linguistic inquiry.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Subfields of the discipline include language change and grammaticalization.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Historical linguistics studies language change either diachronically (through a comparison of different time periods in the past and present) or in a synchronic manner (by observing developments between different variations that exist within the current linguistic stage of a language).
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] At first, historical linguistics was the cornerstone of comparative linguistics, which involves a study of the relationship between different languages.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] At that time, scholars of historical linguistics were only concerned with creating different categories of language families, and reconstructing prehistoric proto-languages by using both the comparative method and the method of internal reconstruction.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Internal reconstruction is the method by which an element that contains a certain meaning is re-used in different contexts or environments where there is a variation in either sound or analogy.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] The reason for this had been to describe well-known Indo-European languages, many of which had detailed documentation and long written histories.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Scholars of historical linguistics also studied Uralic languages, another European language family for which very little written material existed back then.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] After that, there also followed significant work on the corpora of other languages, such as the Austronesian languages and the Native American language families.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] In historical work, the uniformitarian principle is generally the underlying working hypothesis, occasionally also clearly expressed.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] The above approach of comparativism in linguistics is now, however, only a small part of the much broader discipline called historical linguistics.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] For instance, some scholars also tried to establish super-families, linking, for example, Indo-European, Uralic, and other language families to a hypothetical Nostratic language group.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] These attempts are still not widely accepted as credible methods.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] A limit of around 10,000 years is often assumed for the functional purpose of conducting research.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] It is also hard to date various proto-languages.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Even though several methods are available, these languages can be dated only approximately.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] In modern historical linguistics, we examine how languages change over time, focusing on the relationships between dialects within a specific period.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] This includes studying morphological, syntactical, and phonetic shifts.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Connections between dialects in the past and present are also explored.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Syntax is the study of how words and morphemes combine to form larger units such as phrases and sentences.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Central concerns of syntax include word order, grammatical relations, constituency, agreement, the nature of crosslinguistic variation, and the relationship between form and meaning.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] There are numerous approaches to syntax that differ in their central assumptions and goals.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Morphology is the study of words, including the principles by which they are formed, and how they relate to one another within a language.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Most approaches to morphology investigate the structure of words in terms of *morphemes*, which are the smallest units in a language with some independent meaning.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Morphemes include roots that can exist as words by themselves, but also categories such as affixes that can only appear as part of a larger word.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] For example, in English the root *catch* and the suffix *-ing* are both morphemes; *catch* may appear as its own word, or it may be combined with *-ing* to form the new word *catching*.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Morphology also analyzes how words behave as parts of speech, and how they may be inflected to express grammatical categories including number, tense, and aspect.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Concepts such as productivity are concerned with how speakers create words in specific contexts, which evolves over the history of a language.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] The discipline that deals specifically with the sound changes occurring within morphemes is morphophonology.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Semantics and pragmatics are branches of linguistics concerned with meaning.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] These subfields have traditionally been divided according to aspects of meaning: "semantics" refers to grammatical and lexical meanings, while "pragmatics" is concerned with meaning in context.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Within linguistics, the subfield of formal semantics studies the denotations of sentences and how they are composed from the meanings of their constituent expressions.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Formal semantics draws heavily on philosophy of language and uses formal tools from logic and computer science.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] On the other hand, cognitive semantics explains linguistic meaning via aspects of general cognition, drawing on ideas from cognitive science such as prototype theory.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Pragmatics focuses on phenomena such as speech acts, implicature, and talk in interaction.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Phonetics and phonology are branches of linguistics concerned with sounds (or the equivalent aspects of sign languages).
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Phonetics is largely concerned with the physical aspects of sounds such as their articulation, acoustics, production, and perception.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Phonology is concerned with the linguistic abstractions and categorizations of sounds, and it tells us what sounds are in a language, how they do and can combine into words, and explains why certain phonetic features are important to identifying a word.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Linguistic typology (or language typology) is a field of linguistics that studies and classifies languages according to their structural features to allow their comparison.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Its aim is to describe and explain the structural diversity and the common properties of the world's languages.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Its subdisciplines include, but are not limited to: phonological typology, which deals with sound features; syntactic typology, which deals with word order and form; lexical typology, which deals with language vocabulary; and theoretical typology, which aims to explain the universal tendencies.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Linguistic structures are pairings of meaning and form.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Any particular pairing of meaning and form is a Saussurean linguistic sign.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] For instance, the meaning "cat" is represented worldwide with a wide variety of different sound patterns (in oral languages), movements of the hands and face (in sign languages), and written symbols (in written languages).
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Linguistic patterns have proven their importance for the knowledge engineering field especially with the ever-increasing amount of available data.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Linguists focusing on structure attempt to understand the rules regarding language use that native speakers know (not always consciously).
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] All linguistic structures can be broken down into component parts that are combined according to (sub)conscious rules, over multiple levels of analysis.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] For instance, consider the structure of the word "tenth" on two different levels of analysis.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] On the level of internal word structure (known as morphology), the word "tenth" is made up of one linguistic form indicating a number and another form indicating ordinality.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] The rule governing the combination of these forms ensures that the ordinality marker "th" follows the number "ten".
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] On the level of sound structure (known as phonology), structural analysis shows that the "n" sound in "tenth" is made differently from the "n" sound in "ten" spoken alone.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Although most speakers of English are consciously aware of the rules governing internal structure of the word pieces of "tenth", they are less often aware of the rule governing its sound structure.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Linguists focused on structure find and analyze rules such as these, which govern how native speakers use language.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Grammar is a system of rules which governs the production and use of utterances in a given language.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] These rules apply to sound as well as meaning, and include componential subsets of rules, such as those pertaining to phonology (the organization of phonetic sound systems), morphology (the formation and composition of words), and syntax (the formation and composition of phrases and sentences).
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Modern frameworks that deal with the principles of grammar include structural and functional linguistics, and generative linguistics.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Discourse is language as social practice (Baynham, 1995) and is a multilayered concept.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] As a social practice, discourse embodies different ideologies through written and spoken texts.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Discourse analysis can examine or expose these ideologies.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Discourse not only influences genre, which is selected based on specific contexts but also, at a micro level, shapes language as text (spoken or written) down to the phonological and lexico-grammatical levels.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Grammar and discourse are linked as parts of a system.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] A particular discourse becomes a language variety when it is used in this way for a particular purpose, and is referred to as a register.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] There may be certain lexical additions (new words) that are brought into play because of the expertise of the community of people within a certain domain of specialization.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Thus, registers and discourses distinguish themselves not only through specialized vocabulary but also, in some cases, through distinct stylistic choices.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] People in the medical fraternity, for example, may use some medical terminology in their communication that is specialized to the field of medicine.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] This is often referred to as being part of the "medical discourse", and so on.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] The lexicon is a catalogue of words and terms that are stored in a speaker's mind.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] The lexicon consists of words and bound morphemes, which are parts of words that can not stand alone, like affixes.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] In some analyses, compound words and certain classes of idiomatic expressions and other collocations are also considered to be part of the lexicon.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Dictionaries represent attempts at listing, in alphabetical order, the lexicon of a given language; usually, however, bound morphemes are not included.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Lexicography, closely linked with the domain of semantics, is the science of mapping the words into an encyclopedia or a dictionary.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] The creation and addition of new words (into the lexicon) is called coining or neologization, and the new words are called neologisms.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] It is often believed that a speaker's capacity for language lies in the quantity of words stored in the lexicon.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] However, this is often considered a myth by linguists.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] The capacity for the use of language is considered by many linguists to lie primarily in the domain of grammar, and to be linked with competence, rather than with the growth of vocabulary.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Even a very small lexicon is theoretically capable of producing an infinite number of sentences.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Vocabulary size is relevant as a measure of comprehension.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] There is general consensus that reading comprehension of a written text in English requires 98% coverage, meaning that the person understands 98% of the words in the text.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] The question of how much vocabulary is needed is therefore related to which texts or conversations need to be understood.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] A common estimate is 6-7,000 word families to understand a wide range of conversations and 8-9,000 word families to be able to read a wide range of written texts.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Stylistics also involves the study of written, signed, or spoken discourse through varying speech communities, genres, and editorial or narrative formats in the mass media.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] It involves the study and interpretation of texts for aspects of their linguistic and tonal style.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Stylistic analysis entails the analysis of description of particular dialects and registers used by speech communities.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Stylistic features include rhetoric, diction, stress, satire, irony, dialogue, and other forms of phonetic variations.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Stylistic analysis can also include the study of language in canonical works of literature, popular fiction, news, advertisements, and other forms of communication in popular culture as well.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] It is usually seen as a variation in communication that changes from speaker to speaker and community to community.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] In short, Stylistics is the interpretation of text.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] In the 1960s, Jacques Derrida, for instance, further distinguished between speech and writing, by proposing that written language be studied as a linguistic medium of communication in itself.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Palaeography is therefore the discipline that studies the evolution of written scripts (as signs and symbols) in language.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Modern linguistics is primarily descriptive.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Linguists describe and explain features of language without making subjective judgments on whether a particular feature or usage is "good" or "bad".
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] This is analogous to practice in other sciences: a zoologist studies the animal kingdom without making subjective judgments on whether a particular species is "better" or "worse" than another.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Prescription, on the other hand, is an attempt to promote particular linguistic usages over others, often favoring a particular dialect or "acrolect".
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] This may have the aim of establishing a linguistic standard, which can aid communication over large geographical areas.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] It may also, however, be an attempt by speakers of one language or dialect to exert influence over speakers of other languages or dialects (see Linguistic imperialism).
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] An extreme version of prescriptivism can be found among censors, who attempt to eradicate words and structures that they consider to be destructive to society.
[src:cornelia-müller/linguist] Prescription, however, may be practised appropriately in language instruction, like in ELT, where certain fundamental grammatical rules and lexical items need to be introduced to a second-language speaker who is attempting to acquire the language.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] A **metaphor** is a figure of speech that, for literary effect, refers to one thing by mentioning another.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Thus, it invites the audience to make a comparison between two normally unrelated entities or ideas, which may provide clarity or identify hidden similarities between them.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Metaphors are usually meant to create a likeness or an analogy.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Scholars group metaphors with other types of figurative language, such as hyperbole and metonymy.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Metaphors are most similar to similes, except in metaphor the comparison is implied or assumed whereas the extra wording of a simile makes the comparison more obvious or explicit.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] This quotation expresses a metaphor because the world is not literally a stage, and most humans are not literally actors and actresses playing roles.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] By asserting that the world is a stage, Shakespeare uses points of comparison between the world and a stage to convey an understanding about the mechanics of the world and the behavior of the people within it.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Some recent linguistic theories view all language in essence as metaphorical.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] The etymology of a word may uncover a metaphorical usage which has since become obscured with persistent use - such as for example the English word "window", etymologically equivalent to "wind eye".
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] The word*metaphor* itself is a metaphor, coming from a Greek term meaning 'transference (of ownership)'.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] The user of a metaphor alters the reference of the word, "carrying" it from one semantic "realm" to another.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] The new meaning of the word might derive from an analogy between the two semantic realms, but also from other reasons such as the distortion of the semantic realm - for example in sarcasm.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Other writers employ the general terms *ground* and *figure* to denote the tenor and the vehicle.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Cognitive linguistics uses the terms *target* and *source*, respectively.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Psychologist Julian Jaynes coined the terms *metaphrand* and *metaphier*, plus two new concepts, *paraphrand* and *paraphier*.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] *Metaphrand* is equivalent to the metaphor-theory terms *tenor*, *target*, and *ground*.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] *Metaphier* is equivalent to the metaphor-theory terms *vehicle*, *figure*, and *source*.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] In a simple metaphor, an obvious attribute of the metaphier exactly characterizes the metaphrand (e.g.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] For example, in the metaphor "Pat is a tornado", the metaphrand is *Pat*; the metaphier is *tornado*.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] As metaphier, *tornado* carries paraphiers such as power, storm and wind, counterclockwise motion, and danger, threat, destruction, etc.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] The metaphoric meaning of *tornado* is inexact: one might understand that 'Pat is powerfully destructive' through the paraphrand of physical and emotional destruction; another person might understand the metaphor as 'Pat can spin out of control'.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] In the latter case, the paraphier of 'spinning motion' has become the paraphrand 'psychological spin', suggesting an entirely new metaphor for emotional unpredictability, a possibly apt description for a human being hardly applicable to a tornado.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Based on his analysis, Jaynes claims that metaphors not only enhance description, but "increase enormously our powers of perception...and our understanding of [the world], and literally create new objects".
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Metaphors are most frequently compared with similes.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] A metaphor asserts the objects in the comparison are identical on the point of comparison, while a simile merely asserts a similarity through use of words such as *like* or *as*.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] For this reason a common-type metaphor is generally considered more forceful than a simile.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Metaphor is distinct from metonymy, as the two concepts embody different fundamental modes of thought.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Metaphor works by bringing together concepts from different conceptual domains, whereas metonymy uses one element from a given domain to refer to another closely related element.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] A metaphor creates new links between otherwise distinct conceptual domains, whereas a metonymy relies on pre-existent links within such domains.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] For example, in the phrase "lands belonging to the crown", the word *crown* is a **metonymy** because some monarchs do indeed wear a crown, physically.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] In other words, there is a pre-existent link between *crown* and *monarchy*.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] On the other hand, when Ghil'ad Zuckermann argues that the Israeli language is a "phoenicuckoo cross with some magpie characteristics", he is using **metaphor**.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] There is no physical link between a language and a bird.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Furthermore, the metaphor *magpie* is employed because, according to Zuckermann, hybridic *Israeli* displays the characteristics of a magpie, "stealing" from languages such as Arabic and English.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] A dead metaphor is a metaphor in which the sense of a transferred image has become absent.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] The phrases "to grasp a concept" and "to gather what you've understood" use physical action as a metaphor for understanding.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] The audience does not need to visualize the action; dead metaphors normally go unnoticed.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Some distinguish between a dead metaphor and a cliché.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Others use "dead metaphor" to denote both.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] An extended metaphor, or conceit, sets up a principal subject with several subsidiary subjects or comparisons.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] In the above quote from *As You Like It*, the world is first described as a stage and then the subsidiary subjects men and women are further described in the same context.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] An implicit metaphor has no specified tenor, although the vehicle is present.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Abrams offers the following as an example of an implicit metaphor: "That reed was too frail to survive the storm of its sorrows".
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] The reed is the vehicle for the implicit tenor, someone's death, and the storm is the vehicle for the person's sorrows.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Metaphor can serve as a device for persuading an audience of the user's argument or thesis, the so-called rhetorical metaphor.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] The term absolute metaphor describes the special case of a metaphor that has become independent of the facts it illustrates.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] It was coined by the German philosopher Hans Blumenberg in the context of his collaboration on the project of history of concepts (German: *Begriffsgeschichte*).
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Metaphors, according to Aristotle, have "qualities of the exotic and the fascinating; but at the same time we recognize that strangers do not have the same rights as our fellow citizens".
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Educational psychologist Andrew Ortony gives more explicit detail: "Metaphors are necessary as a communicative device because they allow the transfer of coherent chunks of characteristics – perceptual, cognitive, emotional and experiential – from a vehicle which is known to a topic which is less so.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] As a characteristic of speech and writing, metaphors can serve the poetic imagination.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] This allows Sylvia Plath, in her poem "Cut", to compare the blood issuing from her cut thumb to the running of a million soldiers, "redcoats, every one"; and enabling Robert Frost, in "The Road Not Taken", to compare a life to a journey.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Metaphors can be implied and extended throughout pieces of literature.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Foss characterizes metaphors as "nonliteral comparisons in which a word or phrase from one domain of experience is applied to another domain".
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] She argues that since reality is mediated by the language we use to describe it, the metaphors we use shape the world and our interactions to it.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Some theorists have suggested that metaphors are not merely stylistic, but are also cognitively important.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] In *Metaphors We Live By* (1980), George Lakoff and Mark Johnson argue that metaphors are pervasive in everyday life, not only in language but also in thought and action.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] A common definition of metaphor presents it as a comparison that shows how two things, which are not alike in most ways, are similar in another important way.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] In this context, metaphors contribute to the creation of multiple meanings within polysemic complexes across different languages.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Furthermore, Lakoff and Johnson explain that a metaphor is essentially the understanding and experiencing of one kind of thing in terms of another, which they refer to as a "conduit metaphor".
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] According to this view, a speaker can put ideas or objects into containers and then send them along a conduit to a listener, who removes the object from the container to make meaning of it.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Thus, communication is conceptualized as something that ideas flow into, with the container being separate from the ideas themselves.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Lakoff and Johnson provide several examples of daily metaphors in use, including "argument is war" and "time is money".
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] These metaphors occur widely in various contexts to express personal meanings.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Moreover, experimental evidence shows that "priming" people with material from one area can influence how they perform tasks and interpret language in a metaphorically related area.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Omnipresent metaphor may provide an indicator for researching the functionality of language.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] For example: one *devours* a book of *raw* facts, tries to *digest* them, *stews* over them, lets them *simmer on the back-burner*, *regurgitates* them in discussions, and *cooks* up explanations, hoping they do not seem *half-baked*.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] From a sociological, cultural, or philosophical perspective, one asks to what extent ideologies maintain and impose conceptual patterns of thought by introducing, supporting, and adapting fundamental patterns of thinking metaphorically.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] The question is to what extent the ideology fashion and refashion the idea of the nation as a container with borders, and how enemies and outsiders are represented.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Some cognitive scholars have attempted to take on board the idea that different languages have evolved radically different concepts and conceptual metaphors, while others hold to the Sapir-Whorf hypothesis.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] German philologist Wilhelm von Humboldt (1767–1835) contributed significantly to this debate on the relationship between culture, language, and linguistic communities.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Humboldt remains, however, relatively unknown in English-speaking nations.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Andrew Goatly, in "Washing the Brain", takes on board the dual problem of conceptual metaphor as a framework implicit in the language as a system and the way individuals and ideologies negotiate conceptual metaphors.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Neural biological research suggests that some metaphors are innate, as demonstrated by reduced metaphorical understanding in psychopathy.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Underhill, in *Creating Worldviews: Ideology, Metaphor & Language* (Edinburgh UP), considers the way individual speech adopts and reinforces certain metaphoric paradigms.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] This involves a critique of both communist and fascist discourse.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Underhill's studies are situated in Czech and German, which allows him to demonstrate the ways individuals are thinking both within and resisting the modes by which ideologies seek to appropriate key concepts such as "the people", "the state", "history", and "struggle".
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Though metaphors can be considered to be "in" language, Underhill's chapter on French, English and ethnolinguistics demonstrates that language or languages cannot be conceived of in anything other than metaphoric terms.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Several other philosophers have embraced the view that metaphors may also be described as examples of a linguistic "category mistake" which have the potential of leading unsuspecting users into considerable obfuscation of thought within the realm of epistemology.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Included among them is the Australian philosopher Colin Murray Turbayne.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] In his book *The Myth of Metaphor*, Turbayne argues that the use of metaphor is an essential component within the context of any language system which claims to embody richness and depth of understanding.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] He argues further that the philosophical concept of "substance" or "substratum" has limited meaning at best and that physicalist theories of the universe depend upon mechanistic metaphors which are drawn from deductive logic in the development of their hypotheses.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] By interpreting such metaphors literally, Turbayne argues that modern man has unknowingly fallen victim to only one of several metaphorical models of the universe which may be more beneficial in nature.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] In his book *In Other Shoes: Music, Metaphor, Empathy, Existence* Kendall Walton also places the formulation of metaphors at the center of a "Game of Make Believe," which is regulated by tacit norms and rules.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] These "principles of generation" serve to determine several aspects of the game which include: what is considered to be fictional or imaginary, as well as the fixed function which is assumed by both objects and people who interact in the game.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Walton refers to such generators as "props" which can serve as means to the development of various imaginative ends.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] In "content oriented" games, users derive value from such props as a result of the intrinsic fictional content which they help to create through their participation in the game.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] As familiar examples of such content oriented games, Walton points to putting on a play of *Hamlet* or "playing cops and robbers".
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Walton further argues, however, that not all games conform to this characteristic.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] In the course of creating fictions through the use of metaphor we can also perceive and manipulate props into new improvised representations of something entirely different in a game of "make-believe".
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Suddenly the properties of the props themselves take on primary importance.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] In the process the participants in the game may be only partially conscious of the "prop oriented" nature of the game itself.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Metaphors can map experience between two nonlinguistic realms.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Meyer demonstrated how purely rhythmic and harmonic events can express human emotions.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Art theorist Robert Vischer argued that when we look at a painting, we "feel ourselves into it" by imagining our body in the posture of a nonhuman or inanimate object in the painting.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] For example, the painting *The Lonely Tree* by Caspar David Friedrich shows a tree with contorted, barren limbs.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Looking at the painting, some recipients may imagine their limbs in a similarly contorted and barren shape, evoking a feeling of strain and distress.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Nonlinguistic metaphors may be the foundation of our experience of visual and musical art, as well as dance and other art forms.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] In historical onomasiology or in historical linguistics, a metaphor is defined as a semantic change based on a similarity in form or function between the original concept and the target concept named by a word.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] For example, *mouse*: "small, gray rodent with a long tail" → "small, gray computer device with a long cord".
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Some recent linguistic theories hold that language evolved from the capability of the brain to create metaphors that link actions and sensations to sounds.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Aristotle discusses the creation of metaphors at the end of his *Poetics*: "But the greatest thing by far is to be a master of metaphor.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Baroque literary theorist Emanuele Tesauro defines the metaphor "the most witty and acute, the most strange and marvelous, the most pleasant and useful, the most eloquent and fecund part of the human intellect".
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] There is, he suggests, something divine in metaphor: the world itself is God's poem and metaphor is not just a literary or rhetorical figure but an analytic tool that can penetrate the mysteries of God and His creation.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Friedrich Nietzsche makes metaphor the conceptual center of his early theory of society in *On Truth and Lies in the Non-Moral Sense*.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Some sociologists have found his essay useful for thinking about metaphors used in society and for reflecting on their own use of metaphor.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Sociologists of religion note the importance of metaphor in religious worldviews, and that it is impossible to think sociologically about religion without metaphor.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Psychological research has shown that metaphors influence perception, reasoning, and decision-making by shaping how people conceptualize abstract ideas.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Studies in cognitive linguistics suggest that metaphors are not merely stylistic devices but fundamental to human cognition, as they structure the way people understand and interact with the world.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Experiments demonstrate that different metaphorical framings can alter judgment and behavior.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] For example, a study by Thibodeau and Boroditsky (2011) found that describing crime as a "beast preying on the city" led participants to support more punitive law enforcement policies, whereas framing crime as a "virus infecting the city" increased support for social reform and prevention measures.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Similarly, studies on political discourse suggest that metaphors shape attitudes toward policy decisions, with metaphors like "tax relief" implying that taxation is an inherent burden, thus influencing public opinion.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Metaphors also play a crucial role in how people experience crises, such as the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] (2024) analyzed the use of metaphorical imagery in professional healthcare literature and found that metaphors significantly influenced how healthcare workers perceived and emotionally responded to the pandemic.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Their research identified different categories of metaphorical framings—such as war metaphors ("fighting the pandemic") and transformational metaphors ("lessons learned from the crisis")—which led to varying emotional responses among healthcare workers.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] While war metaphors were widely used, they could also induce feelings of helplessness if the metaphor implied an unwinnable battle.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] In contrast, metaphors that framed the pandemic as a challenge or learning opportunity tended to promote a sense of empowerment and resilience.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] These findings align with previous research showing that metaphors can significantly impact emotional processing and coping strategies in stressful situations.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] Moreover, metaphorical language can impact emotions and mental health.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] For instance, describing depression as "drowning" or "a dark cloud" can intensify the emotional experience of distress, while framing it as "a journey with obstacles" can encourage resilience and problem-solving approaches.
[src:cornelia-müller/metaphor] These findings highlight the pervasive role of metaphors in shaping thought processes, reinforcing the idea that language not only reflects but also constructs reality.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] In linguistics and the philosophy of language, **pragmatics** is the study of how context contributes to meaning.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] This field of study evaluates how human language is utilized in social interactions, as well as the relationship between the interpreter and the interpreted.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Linguists who specialize in pragmatics are called **pragmaticians**.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The field has been represented since 1986 by the International Pragmatics Association (IPrA).
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Pragmatics encompasses phenomena including implicature, speech acts, relevance and conversation, as well as nonverbal communication.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Theories of pragmatics are closely linked to theories of semantics, which studies aspects of meaning, and syntax, which examines sentence structures, principles, and relationships.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Pragmatics, together with semantics and syntactics, is a part of semiotics.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The ability to understand another speaker's intended meaning is called *pragmatic competence*.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] In 1938, Charles Morris first distinguished pragmatics as an independent subfield within semiotics, alongside syntax and semantics.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Pragmatics emerged as its own subfield in the 1950s after the pioneering work of J.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The intellectual roots of pragmatics trace back to early 20th-century philosophy and semiotics.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The term *pragmatics* was first introduced by the semiotician Charles Morris in 1938, when he proposed dividing the study of signs (semiology) into three parts: syntax, semantics, and **pragmatics**.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] In Morris's formulation, pragmatics would specifically study the relationship between signs and their interpreters (i.e. language users), bringing an external perspective that considers users' context and responses.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] This idea was influenced by the philosophical tradition of pragmatism (especially the work of C.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Peirce and colleagues), which emphasized practical consequences and usage in meaning.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Mid-century logical philosophers like Rudolf Carnap built on Morris's approach by suggesting that pragmatics should explicitly analyze the interaction between language, speakers, and the referents of words, thereby making the study of meaning more context-sensitive.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Around the same time, Yehoshua Bar-Hillel (a student of Carnap) argued that certain "indexical" elements of language – words like *I*, *here*, and *now* whose reference shifts with context – must be a central focus of pragmatics.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] These early insights laid a foundation for viewing meaning as fundamentally tied to context and use, even before pragmatics was recognized as a distinct linguistic discipline.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] In the mid-20th century, a broader "pragmatic turn" took place in the study of language, largely driven by philosophers of language examining how meaning depends on use.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The later philosophy of Ludwig Wittgenstein (esp.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] *Philosophical Investigations*, 1953) encapsulated this shift with the dictum that "meaning is use," suggesting that words only gain meaning through their function in language games (concrete social interactions).
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Around the same period, ordinary language philosophers at Oxford began analyzing language not just as an abstract system but as actions performed in particular contexts.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Austin, who in the 1950s developed Speech Act Theory.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Austin's posthumously published lectures *How to Do Things with Words* (1962) demonstrated that utterances can *perform* actions (for example, saying "I apologize" is the act of apologizing) and distinguished different levels of speech acts (the locutionary, illocutionary, and perlocutionary acts).
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] His colleague John Searle extended this framework in the late 1960s, elaborating a taxonomy of speech act types and the rules governing acts like asserting, questioning, commanding, etc., thereby firmly establishing speech acts as a core topic in pragmatics.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The 1967 book *Pragmatics of Human Communication: A Study of Interactional Patterns, Pathologies, and Paradoxes* by Paul Watzlawick, Janet Helmick Beavin, and Don D.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Jackson, is an early book that featured the word *pragmatics* in its title, but it was used in its own interpretation of Morris's earlier conception of the word.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The book is not about linguistics, but rather about psychology and family therapy.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The book relates to Morris's idea of pragmatics because it considers, broadly speaking, how communication is affected by context; the focus of the book, however, is rather on how communication is affected by different participants interpreting whose behavior was caused by whose in different ways.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] For instance, one example in the book is that of a husband saying "I withdraw because she nags" and the wife saying "I nag because he withdraws"; a different example is the husband saying he does not act because the wife dominates, and the wife saying she takes over because the husband is passive.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The book would later influence research on psychotherapy and interpersonal communication, as well as the four-sides model, but not linguistics.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] A key figure in linguistic pragmatics, H.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Paul Grice, advanced the study of pragmatics in the late 1960s and 1970s by explaining how people *mean* more than they literally say.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Grice's theory of conversational implicature (first presented in lectures in 1967, published 1975) proposed that speakers and hearers are guided by a cooperative principle and a set of rational conversational maxims (e.g.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] *be truthful*, *be relevant*, *be brief*, *be clear*).
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] By adhering to or deliberately flouting these maxims, speakers can imply additional meanings which listeners infer in context.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] For example, if Alice asks, "Can you pass the salt?" and Bob responds, "There's a salt shaker on the table," Bob's literal statement is simply informative, but pragmatically it *implies* an answer (affirming that he *can* pass the salt) without directly saying so.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The pioneering contributions of Austin (on speech acts) and Grice (on implicature and conversation) in the 1950s–1970s are often credited with establishing pragmatics as its own subfield within linguistics.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Indeed, before this period, many aspects of meaning that depend on context had been regarded as outside the scope of linguistic theory, but Austin and Grice showed these could be studied systematically.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] In the 1970s, pragmatics began to gain broader recognition among linguists as a necessary complement to syntax and semantics; in Boston in 1970, the International Symposium on the Pragmatics of Natural Language was held.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Pragmatics emerged to address this "leftover" territory: those aspects of meaning and understanding that require speaker intentions, listener inferences, and real-world knowledge.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] During this time, two different scholarly traditions in pragmatics crystallized.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The first was the Anglo-American tradition, rooted in analytic philosophy of language and exemplified by the work of Austin, Searle, Grice, and their followers.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The second was a European continental approach (sometimes called the perspective or functional view of pragmatics), which treated pragmatics as a more holistic perspective on all language behavior, influenced by fields like sociology and anthropology.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Despite differing emphases – the Anglo-American school often analyzing micro-level utterances and logical inference, and the Continental school viewing pragmatics as a general functional dimension of language – both contributed to the growth of the field in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] These milestones marked pragmatics' definitive emergence as an independent discipline within linguistics, concerned specifically with language use and contextual meaning.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Introductory textbooks and handbooks generally converge on the idea that pragmatics investigates how language users encode and infer meanings in context, going beyond sentence-level meaning to recover speakers' intentions and manage social relations.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] These areas are not mutually exclusive; specific phenomena such as deixis, politeness strategies, or scalar implicatures often involve several of them at once, and different theoretical traditions emphasize different subsets of pragmatic concerns.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Ambiguity refers to when it is difficult to infer meaning without knowing the context, the identity of the speaker or the speaker's intent.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Another example of an ambiguous sentence is, "I went to the bank." This is an example of lexical ambiguity, as the word bank can either be in reference to a place where money is kept, or the edge of a river.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] To understand what the speaker is truly saying, it is a matter of context, which is why it is pragmatically ambiguous as well.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Similarly, the sentence "Sherlock saw the man with binoculars" could mean that Sherlock observed the man by using binoculars, or it could mean that Sherlock observed a man who was holding binoculars (*syntactic ambiguity*).
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The meaning of the sentence depends on an understanding of the context and the speaker's intent.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] As defined in linguistics, a sentence is an abstract entity: a string of words divorced from non-linguistic context, as opposed to an utterance, which is a concrete example of a speech act in a specific context.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The more closely conscious subjects stick to common words, idioms, phrasings, and topics, the more easily others can surmise their meaning; the further they stray from common expressions and topics, the wider the variations in interpretations.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] That suggests that sentences do not have intrinsic meaning, that there is no meaning associated with a sentence or word, and that either can represent an idea only symbolically.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] *The cat sat on the mat* is a sentence in English.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] If someone were to say to someone else, "The cat sat on the mat", the act is itself an utterance.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] That implies that a sentence, term, expression or word cannot symbolically represent a single true meaning; such meaning is underspecified (which cat sat on which mat?) and potentially ambiguous.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] By contrast, the meaning of an utterance can be inferred through knowledge of both its linguistic and non-linguistic contexts (which may or may not be sufficient to resolve ambiguity).
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] In mathematics, with Berry's paradox, there arises a similar systematic ambiguity with the word "definable".
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The referential uses of language are how signs are used to refer to certain items.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] A sign is the link or relationship between a signified and the signifier as defined by de Saussure and Jean-René Huguenin.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The signified is some entity or concept in the world.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The relationship between the two gives the sign meaning.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The relationship can be explained further by considering what is meant by *meaning*.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] In pragmatics, there are two different types of meaning to consider: **semantic-referential meaning** and **indexical meaning**.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Semantic-referential meaning refers to the aspect of meaning, which describes events in the world that are independent of the circumstance they are uttered in.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] In this case, the proposition is describing that Santa Claus eats cookies.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The meaning of the proposition does not rely on whether or not Santa Claus is eating cookies at the time of its utterance.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Santa Claus could be eating cookies at any time and the meaning of the proposition would remain the same.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The meaning is simply describing something that is the case in the world.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] In contrast, the proposition, "Santa Claus is eating a cookie right now", describes events that are happening at the time the proposition is uttered.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] If someone were to say that a tiger is a carnivorous animal in one context and a mammal in another, the definition of tiger would still be the same.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The meaning of the sign tiger is describing some animal in the world, which does not change in either circumstance.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Indexical meaning, on the other hand, is dependent on the context of the utterance and has rules of use.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] By rules of use, it is meant that indexicals can tell when they are used, but not what they actually mean.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Whom *I* refers to depends on the context and the person uttering it.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] As mentioned, these meanings are brought about through the relationship between the signified and the signifier.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Referential indexical signs are signs where the meaning shifts depending on the context, hence the nickname *shifters*.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] *I* would be considered a referential indexical sign.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The referential aspect of its meaning would be 'first-person singular' while the indexical aspect would be the person who is speaking (refer above for definitions of semantic-referential and indexical meaning).
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] A pure indexical sign does not contribute to the meaning of the propositions at all.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] A second way to define the signified and signifier relationship is C.S.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] These relationships allow signs to be used to convey intended meaning.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Referring to things and people is a common feature of conversation, and conversants do so collaboratively.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Individuals engaging in discourse utilize pragmatics.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] In addition, individuals within the scope of discourse cannot help but avoid intuitive use of certain utterances or word choices in an effort to create communicative success.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The study of referential language is heavily focused upon definite descriptions and referent accessibility.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Theories have been presented for why direct referent descriptions occur in discourse.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Referential expressions are a form of anaphora.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] They are also a means of connecting past and present thoughts together to create context for information at hand.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Analyzing the context of a sentence and determining whether or not the use of referent expression is necessary is highly reliant upon the author/speaker's digression- and is correlated strongly with the use of pragmatic competency.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The sorts of contexts that such indexes can mark are varied.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] In all of these cases, the semantico-referential meaning of the utterances is unchanged from that of the other possible (but often impermissible) forms, but the pragmatic meaning is vastly different.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Austin introduced the concept of the performative, contrasted in his writing with "constative" (i.e. descriptive) utterances.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] To be performative, an utterance must conform to various conditions involving what Austin calls felicity.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] These deal with things like appropriate context and the speaker's authority.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] There has been a great amount of discussion on the boundary between semantics and pragmatics and there are many different formalizations of aspects of pragmatics linked to context dependence.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Particularly interesting cases are the discussions on the semantics of indexicals and the problem of referential descriptions, a topic developed after the theories of Keith Donnellan.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] A proper logical theory of formal pragmatics has been developed by Carlo Dalla Pozza, according to which it is possible to connect classical semantics (treating propositional contents as true or false) and intuitionistic semantics (dealing with illocutionary forces).
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The presentation of a formal treatment of pragmatics appears to be a development of the Fregean idea of assertion sign as formal sign of the act of assertion.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Over the past decade, many probabilistic and Bayesian methods have become very popular in the modelling of pragmatics, of which the most successful framework has been the Rational Speech Act framework developed by Noah Goodman and Michael C.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Frank, which has already seen much use in the analysis of metaphor, hyperbole and politeness.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Recent work in Artificial Intelligence adds to the RSA framework explicit models (theories of mind (ToMs), $\theta$ , below) the listener and the speaker have of each other.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The models are recursively nested (up to level i , below) partially observable Markov decision processes (POMDPs), called Interactive POMDPs (IPOMDPs).
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] They formalize how agents keep track of (maintain their beliefs about) the state of the world, about each other, and about each other's beliefs.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Including the agents' capability to communicate leads to Communicative IPOMDPs (CIPOMDPs).
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Explicitly defining recursively nested theories of mind allows one to represent how listeners interpret messages they receive by modeling how speakers rationally decide what to communicate.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Conversely, speakers decide what to communicate by modeling the listeners' belief update due to communication, and its effects on the speaker's utility $U_{S}$ .
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The recursion bottoms out after i levels with the literal meaning of utterance u .
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] The ToM nesting level, i , depends on the situation the participants are facing.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Unlike in classical RSA, in CIPOMDPs $U_{S}$ is expressed by the Bellman equation and captures the value of communication as facilitating valuable future interactions.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Note that there is no need to assume the speaker is sincere/cooperative: The listener can use the model of the speaker, $\theta$ , to discount what is communicated if it is in the speaker's interest to be insincere.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] There is considerable overlap between pragmatics and sociolinguistics, since both share an interest in linguistic meaning as determined by usage in a speech community.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] However, sociolinguists tend to be more interested in variations in language within such communities.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Influences of philosophy and politics are also present in the field of pragmatics, as the dynamics of societies and oppression are expressed through language.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Pragmatics helps anthropologists relate elements of language to broader social phenomena; it thus pervades the field of linguistic anthropology.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Because pragmatics describes generally the forces in play for a given utterance, it includes the study of power, gender, race, identity, and their interactions with individual speech acts.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] For example, the study of code-switching directly relates to pragmatics, since a switch in code effects a shift in pragmatic force.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Morris, pragmatics tries to understand the relationship between signs and their users, while semantics tends to focus on the actual objects or ideas to which a word refers, and syntax (or *syntactics*) examines relationships among signs or symbols.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Semantics is the literal meaning of an idea whereas pragmatics is the implied meaning of the given idea.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Austin and further developed by John Searle, centers around the idea of the performative, a type of utterance that performs the very action it describes.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Speech Act Theory's examination of illocutionary acts has many of the same goals as pragmatics, as outlined above.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Computational pragmatics, as defined by Victoria Fromkin, concerns how humans can communicate their intentions to computers with as little ambiguity as possible.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Reference resolution, how a computer determines when two objects are different or not, is one of the most important tasks of computational pragmatics.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Pragmatics (more specifically, Speech Act Theory's notion of the performative) underpins Judith Butler's theory of gender performativity.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Jacques Derrida remarked that some work done under pragmatics aligned well with the program he outlined in his book *Of Grammatology*.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Émile Benveniste argued that the pronouns *I* and *you* are fundamentally distinct from other pronouns because of their role in creating the subject.
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] Gilles Deleuze and Félix Guattari discuss linguistic pragmatics in the fourth chapter of *A Thousand Plateaus* ("November 20, 1923—Postulates of Linguistics").
[src:cornelia-müller/pragmatics] This last conclusion attempts to refute Saussure's division between *langue* and *parole* and Chomsky's distinction between deep structure and surface structure simultaneously.
